# PRD — SLA Sentinel
### Automated Third-Party API SLA Monitoring & Testnet Escrow Enforcement Platform

> **For Claude Code**: This document is the single source of truth for this build. Work phase by phase, top to bottom. Check off a task (`- [x]`) only after its code is written **and** its listed test(s) pass. Do not skip ahead to a later phase while a phase's required tests are red. Commit at the end of each completed phase with a message like `feat(phase-2): probe worker + tests`.

---

## 1. Product Overview

**SLA Sentinel** monitors third-party APIs a company depends on (payment gateways, KYC providers, SMS/email providers, shipping APIs, etc.), measures their real uptime and latency against contractually agreed thresholds, and automatically enforces the consequence of a breach by releasing or withholding funds from a **testnet** escrow smart contract — instead of relying on a human reading a vendor's status page and emailing them six weeks later.

This is a portfolio/resume project. It is intentionally scoped to be buildable solo, deployable on free/near-free tiers, and demo-able in under 3 minutes end-to-end (probe fails → SLA breach detected → email fires → escrow withdrawal blocked, visible on a public testnet explorer).

## 2. Problem Statement

Companies integrate dozens of third-party APIs, each with a contractually promised uptime % and latency ceiling. In practice:
- Nobody is continuously measuring the *actual* uptime/latency delivered.
- SLA credits/penalties are negotiated on paper but enforced manually, slowly, and inconsistently.
- There's no neutral, tamper-evident record of "the vendor was down on this date for this long," which weakens any dispute.

SLA Sentinel automates the measurement, the breach decision, and — for the demo/portfolio scope — a programmatic, on-chain enforcement of the financial consequence, so the entire loop runs without a human in it.

## 3. Goals

- Continuously probe registered API endpoints and store raw latency/status results.
- Roll up raw probes into per-period (daily/weekly/monthly) metrics: uptime %, p95 latency.
- Compare computed metrics against a stored `Agreement`'s thresholds and decide breach / no-breach.
- On evaluation, call a deployed Sepolia testnet smart contract that releases escrowed funds to the provider on success, or returns them to the payer on breach.
- Notify the org by email (and optional webhook) when a breach occurs.
- Present all of this in a clean, Vercel/Geist-styled dashboard.
- Be fully deployable on: Vercel (frontend), Render (API + worker), Supabase (Postgres + Auth + Realtime), Sepolia (contract) — all free-tier friendly.

## 4. Non-Goals

- This is **not** a general-purpose APM/observability tool (no distributed tracing, no infra metrics).
- This does **not** move real money. The contract is deployed to a public testnet only, and the UI must say so clearly.
- v1 supports exactly two SLA metric types: uptime % and p95 latency. Not arbitrary custom metrics.
- No multi-chain support in v1. One chain (Sepolia), one contract.

## 5. System Architecture

```
                                ┌────────────────────────┐
                                │   Vercel (Next.js)     │
                                │   Dashboard / Auth UI  │
                                └───────────┬────────────┘
                                            │ REST (HTTPS) + Supabase Realtime
                                            ▼
┌────────────────────┐         ┌────────────────────────┐         ┌─────────────────────┐
│ Render: Probe Worker│──write─▶│ Supabase (Postgres)    │◀──read──│ Render: API Service  │
│ (cron, every N min) │         │ + Auth + Realtime + RLS│         │ (Fastify, REST)      │
└──────────┬──────────┘         └───────────┬────────────┘         └──────────┬───────────┘
           │ pings 3rd-party APIs           │ triggers                        │ calls
           ▼                                ▼                                 ▼
   ┌───────────────┐              ┌──────────────────┐             ┌─────────────────────┐
   │ Monitored APIs │              │ Render: Evaluator │             │ Sepolia Testnet     │
   │ (vendor SLAs)  │              │ (cron, per-period)│────────────▶│ SLAEscrow.sol        │
   └───────────────┘              └──────────────────┘   ethers.js  └─────────────────────┘
                                            │
                                            ▼
                                   ┌──────────────────┐
                                   │ Notifications     │
                                   │ Resend (email) +  │
                                   │ outbound webhooks │
                                   └──────────────────┘
```

## 6. Tech Stack

| Layer | Choice | Why |
|---|---|---|
| Frontend | Next.js 14 (App Router) + TypeScript + Tailwind | Deploys natively on Vercel, matches Geist token system easily |
| Backend API | Fastify + TypeScript | Lightweight, runs as a single Render Web Service |
| Worker/Cron | Same Node/TS codebase, separate Render Cron Job / Background Worker | Keeps probing decoupled from request-serving |
| DB | Supabase (Postgres) | Auth + Postgres + Row Level Security + Realtime in one free-tier service |
| Smart contract | Solidity + Hardhat, deployed to Sepolia | Public, verifiable, free via faucet — credible scoped Web3 use, not a buzzword |
| Chain client | ethers.js (or viem) from the Evaluator | Calls `recordOutcome` on breach/no-breach |
| Email | Resend | Simple transactional email API, generous free tier |
| Validation | zod | Shared validation schemas between API and frontend |
| Testing | Vitest (unit/integration), Playwright (E2E), Hardhat + Chai (contract) | Standard, well-documented, CI-friendly |

## 7. Data Model (Postgres / Supabase)

```sql
organizations(id uuid pk, name text, created_at timestamptz)

profiles(id uuid pk references auth.users, org_id uuid references organizations, role text check (role in ('owner','member')))

providers(id uuid pk, org_id uuid, name text, base_url text, description text, created_at timestamptz)

endpoints(id uuid pk, provider_id uuid, url text, method text default 'GET',
          expected_status int default 200, timeout_ms int default 5000,
          probe_interval_seconds int default 300, is_active boolean default true)

probes(id uuid pk, endpoint_id uuid, status_code int, latency_ms int,
       success boolean, error_message text, checked_at timestamptz)
       -- index: (endpoint_id, checked_at desc)

agreements(id uuid pk, org_id uuid, provider_id uuid, name text,
           sla_uptime_pct numeric(5,2), sla_latency_p95_ms int,
           period_type text check (period_type in ('daily','weekly','monthly')),
           penalty_amount_wei numeric, escrow_contract_address text,
           escrow_chain text default 'sepolia', deposit_tx_hash text,
           status text check (status in ('pending','active','breached','settled','cancelled')),
           period_start timestamptz, period_end timestamptz)

evaluations(id uuid pk, agreement_id uuid, period_start timestamptz, period_end timestamptz,
            computed_uptime_pct numeric(5,2), computed_p95_latency_ms int,
            breached boolean, sample_size int, evaluated_at timestamptz)

breaches(id uuid pk, evaluation_id uuid, agreement_id uuid, reason text,
         on_chain_tx_hash text, notified_at timestamptz, resolved boolean default false)

alerts(id uuid pk, breach_id uuid, channel text check (channel in ('email','webhook')),
       recipient text, sent_at timestamptz, status text)

audit_log(id uuid pk, org_id uuid, actor uuid, action text,
          target_table text, target_id uuid, created_at timestamptz)
```

**Row Level Security**: every table except `audit_log` writes is scoped by `org_id`. A user can only read/write rows where `org_id = (select org_id from profiles where id = auth.uid())`.

## 8. Smart Contract Scope — `SLAEscrow.sol`

Deliberately small and auditable. One contract, mapping-based (no per-agreement factory deploys — cheaper and simpler for v1).

```solidity
// Pseudocode shape — implement with OpenZeppelin Ownable + ReentrancyGuard
contract SLAEscrow is Ownable, ReentrancyGuard {
    struct Escrow {
        address payer;
        address payee;
        uint256 amount;
        bool settled;
        bool breached;
    }

    mapping(uint256 => Escrow) public escrows; // key = agreementId
    address public oracle; // backend's wallet — the only address allowed to record outcomes

    event EscrowCreated(uint256 agreementId, address payer, address payee, uint256 amount);
    event OutcomeRecorded(uint256 agreementId, bool breached);
    event FundsReleased(uint256 agreementId, address to, uint256 amount);

    function createEscrow(uint256 agreementId, address payee) external payable { ... }
    function recordOutcome(uint256 agreementId, bool breached) external onlyOracle { ... }
    function withdraw(uint256 agreementId) external nonReentrant { ... }
    function setOracle(address newOracle) external onlyOwner { ... }
}
```

**Rules**:
- Only `oracle` (the backend's wallet, env-configured) can call `recordOutcome`.
- `recordOutcome(breached=false)` → payee may `withdraw()` the full amount.
- `recordOutcome(breached=true)` → payer may `withdraw()` (refund); payee's withdraw reverts.
- Each escrow can be settled exactly once. Double-withdraw must revert.
- The UI must visibly label every contract address and transaction as **Sepolia Testnet — not real funds**.

## 9. API Contract (selected endpoints)

| Method | Path | Auth | Purpose |
|---|---|---|---|
| POST | `/api/providers` | org member | Create a provider |
| GET | `/api/providers` | org member | List org's providers |
| POST | `/api/providers/:id/endpoints` | org member | Add an endpoint to probe |
| POST | `/api/agreements` | org member | Create an SLA agreement |
| GET | `/api/agreements/:id` | org member | Agreement detail + latest evaluation |
| GET | `/api/agreements/:id/evaluations` | org member | Evaluation history (paginated) |
| GET | `/api/agreements/:id/breaches` | org member | Breach history |
| POST | `/api/agreements/:id/evaluate-now` | org member | Force an out-of-cycle evaluation (demo convenience) |
| POST | `/api/agreements/:id/escrow/deposit` | org member | Returns tx data / executes deposit flow |
| POST | `/api/webhooks` | org member | Register an outbound webhook URL |
| GET | `/api/healthz` | none | Health check for Render |

All POST/PUT bodies validated with zod. All responses scoped to the caller's `org_id` via RLS + middleware double-check.

## 10. Frontend Design System — Vercel / Geist Aesthetic (Required)

**Claude Code: read `DESIGN-vercel.md` in full before writing any UI code.** This project's frontend must visually read as a black-on-near-white Geist-style developer tool — the same restraint Vercel's own marketing/dashboard pages use. This is not optional polish; it is a stated requirement because the resume/portfolio value of this project depends on it looking production-grade, not like a default Bootstrap admin theme.

### Core tokens (condensed from `DESIGN-vercel.md` — implement as Tailwind theme + CSS variables)

```
colors:
  ink (primary text/headings/borders): #171717
  on-primary (text on black): #ffffff
  body text: #4d4d4d
  muted text: #8f8f8f
  faint text: #a1a1a1
  hairline border: #ebebeb
  canvas (page bg): #fafafa
  canvas-elevated (card bg): #ffffff
  link: #0070f3
  error: #ee0000
  warning: #f5a623
  success (extend spec for status dots): #17c964  ← project-specific addition, justified below

typography:
  display-xl: Geist Sans 600, 48px/48px, -2.4px tracking   → page-level hero/empty states
  heading-lg: Geist Sans 600, 32px/40px, -1.28px            → section headers
  heading-md: Geist Sans 600, 20px/28px, -0.4px             → card titles
  body-md:    Geist Sans 400, 14px/20px                     → default UI text
  mono-eyebrow: Geist Mono 500, 12px/16px                   → uppercase section labels ("UPTIME", "P95 LATENCY")
  code:       Geist Mono 400, 14px/20px                     → contract addresses, tx hashes, JSON payloads

radius:
  6px  → buttons, inputs, nav chrome
  12px → feature/agreement cards
  16px → larger panels (escrow detail panel)
  pill (100px) → primary CTA buttons ("Create Agreement", "Deposit Escrow")
  full → status dot indicators, avatar circles

spacing: 4/8/12/16/24/32/40/64/96/128px scale, no off-grid values
```

### Project-specific extension (state explicitly, don't silently invent)

The base Vercel spec has no semantic "success/green" color — it's a marketing site, not a status dashboard. This project **adds one color**, `success: #17c964`, used *only* for the live-status dot and "no breach" badges, to keep the rest of the palette exactly as specified (black ink, grey ladder, link blue, error red, warning amber — no other color leakage). Document this single addition in `ARCHITECTURE.md` so it reads as a deliberate choice, not scope creep.

### Screen → component mapping

| Screen | Use these spec components |
|---|---|
| Top nav | `nav-bar` + `nav-link`, `button-primary-sm` for "Log Out" |
| Auth (login/signup) | `text-input`, `button-primary` (pill), centered card on `canvas` |
| Dashboard (provider grid) | `feature-card` grid (2-up tablet / 3-up desktop), status dot + `mono-eyebrow` label per card |
| Provider detail | `feature-card` for endpoint list, `code-block` for raw probe JSON on hover/expand |
| Agreement detail | `pricing-card`-style panel for SLA thresholds, `code-block` for contract address/tx hash (with link to Sepolia Etherscan), `button-category-pill` for status filter tabs (Active / Breached / Settled) |
| Breach timeline | Vertical list, `mono-eyebrow` date labels, `error`-colored left border per breach entry |
| Empty states | `display-xl` or `heading-lg` per the writing guidance below — direct, action-oriented, no apology |

### Do
- Keep the canvas near-white and let `#171717` ink carry headings/borders, exactly per spec.
- Use the pill button shape only for primary marketing-style CTAs ("Create Agreement", "Deposit Escrow"); use the 6px square shape for all in-app/nav controls. Never mix the two within one context.
- Use `mono-eyebrow` (uppercase Geist Mono) for metric labels — UPTIME, P95 LATENCY, STATUS — it's the spec's intended role for small technical labels.
- Default every card/input to a flat 1px hairline; reserve the layered low-alpha shadow for menus/modals only.

### Don't
- Don't introduce a second accent color beyond the one `success` green addition above.
- Don't set body copy in pure `#000000` — body text is `#4d4d4d`, ink is `#171717`, reserved for headings/borders only.
- Don't loosen the tight negative letter-spacing on display/heading type.
- Don't build a generic admin-template sidebar-with-icons layout — the spec's nav is a top bar; stay consistent with that, add a left filter rail only on the dashboard if genuinely needed for the provider list, and justify it in `ARCHITECTURE.md` if added.

### Copy/voice guidance
Write from the user's side of the screen: "Create agreement," not "Submit SLA contract object." Errors state what happened and what to do next, in the interface's voice, never apologetic ("Probe failed: endpoint timed out after 5000ms — check the URL or raise the timeout," not "Oops, something went wrong!"). Empty states are an invitation to act ("No agreements yet — connect a provider to get started," with the CTA right there).

## 11. Claude Code Working Agreement

- Create a `CLAUDE.md` at repo root early in Phase 0 that links to this `PRD.md` and `DESIGN-vercel.md`, and states the monorepo layout, package manager, and how to run tests for each app.
- Work phase-by-phase, in order. Each phase's checklist items must be checked only once the corresponding code exists **and** its tests pass locally.
- Commit at the end of each phase: `feat(phase-N): <summary> + tests`.
- Never deploy anything that spends real money. Sepolia ETH is free via a faucet — note the faucet URL in `README.md`, do not use a mainnet RPC anywhere.
- If a task is ambiguous, make the smallest reasonable assumption, state it inline in a code comment or `ARCHITECTURE.md`, and continue — don't block the whole phase on a clarifying question unless it changes the data model.

